Wow! I've read through both parts of your story thoroughly. This is an incredibly ambitious and well-thought-out project! Here are my honest thoughts:

What I Think of Your Story:
Strengths:

Complex Power System: The Resolve system is intricate and well-developed - reminiscent of JJK's cursed energy but with unique mechanics like the Core system, the five manifestation types, and the emotional/conviction-based nature.
Character Depth: You've put serious work into character development. The main trio (Tetsu, Shin, Aka) have compelling dynamics, especially the past-life cycle element and the internal conflict with "The Other."
Emotional Core: The childhood trauma elements (Tetsu's sister, Ren's lost daughter, the family dynamics) give real emotional weight to the story.
World-Building: The Resolvers organization, international scope, grade system, and distinction between Naturals vs Ruptured creates a rich, believable world.
Areas to Consider:

Character Count: You have 32 characters planned. That's... a lot. Even JJK with its ensemble cast took time to introduce characters gradually. Consider which ones are truly essential to the core narrative vs. which could be combined or saved for later arcs.
The "Other" Mystery: The relationship between Tetsu and Aka/The Other is fascinating, but make sure the reveal of their past-life connection pays off emotionally. The Sukuna comparison is apt, but your story needs its own identity.
Shin's Motivation: "I hoped this time would be different" is powerful, but you'll need to carefully balance making him sympathetic while keeping him an obstacle. The best antagonist-allies (like Sasuke) have clear, understandable motivations.
Pacing: With this many moving parts (character arcs, international intrigue, past lives, The Sanctum, power progression), pacing will be crucial. Make sure each arc has a clear focus.
Rating: 8.5/10 as a concept
You've built something with real potential. The emotional beats are there, the power system is engaging, and you're clearly thinking about theme and character growth. With tight execution and careful pacing, this could genuinely stand alongside the manga/anime you're inspired by.

My main advice: Focus on Tetsu, Shin, and Aka first. Get that core relationship perfect. Everything else should orbit around that emotional center. The best shonen stories (JJK, CSM, HxH) succeed because their core relationships are unshakeable, even when the plot gets complex.

Keep writing. You've got something here.

