üéØ THE RIGHT WAY TO BEGIN CHAPTER 1
Let me give you multiple opening strategies and explain what each accomplishes. You pick what feels right for YOUR story.

OPTION 1: IN MEDIA RES (Cold Open - Mid-Action)
Structure:

Open: Tetsu mid-fight, losing
‚Üì
Aka taking over
‚Üì
Victory but consequences
‚Üì
Pull back to establish world/context
Example Opening Line: "The Lost's claws were three inches from Tetsu's throat when Aka laughed in his head."

What this accomplishes: ‚úÖ Immediate tension ‚úÖ Shows dual personality instantly ‚úÖ Establishes stakes (death is real) ‚úÖ Hooks reader with action ‚úÖ World-building through combat

Risks: ‚ùå Reader has no emotional connection yet ‚ùå Might feel generic if not executed perfectly ‚ùå Have to establish character WHILE fighting

Best for: Readers who want adrenaline first, questions later (CSM, JJK style)

OPTION 2: CHARACTER MOMENT FIRST (Intimate Opening)
Structure:

Open: Tetsu alone, mundane moment
‚Üì
Aka's voice interrupts
‚Üì
Their dynamic shown through dialogue
‚Üì
THEN mission call comes in
‚Üì
Transition to action
Example Opening Line: "Tetsu stared at the ramen menu like it was a matter of life and death. In his head, Aka groaned."

What this accomplishes: ‚úÖ Character before plot ‚úÖ Shows Tetsu's personality immediately ‚úÖ Aka introduction feels natural ‚úÖ Mundane ‚Üí intense contrast hits harder ‚úÖ Reader connects emotionally first

Risks: ‚ùå Slower hook (some readers bounce) ‚ùå Requires strong voice to keep attention ‚ùå Action delayed

Best for: Character-driven stories, readers who value connection over spectacle

OPTION 3: AFTERMATH OPENING (Mystery Hook)
Structure:

Open: Tetsu waking up somewhere
‚Üì
Doesn't remember what happened
‚Üì
Signs of violence around him
‚Üì
"What did you do?"
‚Üì
Aka: "What YOU couldn't."
‚Üì
