üî• CHAPTER 1: "TWO CORES"
Writing now. No more delays.

Tetsu was halfway through tying his left boot when Aka's voice cut through his thoughts.

"You're going to die today."

"Good morning to you too," Tetsu muttered, yanking the lace tight.

"I'm serious. You're sloppy when you're tired. And you didn't sleep."

"I slept."

"Three hours isn't sleep, it's a tactical error."

Before Tetsu could respond, the alarm screamed through R7's barracks‚Äîsharp, mechanical, unforgiving.

His hands stopped moving.

"See?" Aka's tone shifted, almost satisfied. "Told you."

The Lost's claws were three inches from Tetsu's throat when he realized Aka might've been right.

"Shit‚Äî"

His Resolve flared instinctively, pale blue barrier flickering to life just as the creature's hand crashed down. The impact drove him into the concrete, cracks spiderwebbing beneath his back. Pain exploded through his chest‚Äînot from the blow, but from his Core compressing under the strain.

"Let me handle this," Aka said, voice calm, almost bored.

"I've got it‚Äî"

"You don't."

The Lost shrieked, pulling back for another strike. Its body was wrong‚Äîskin stretched too tight over bones that bent at angles that shouldn't exist, eyes milky and vacant, jaw distended in a permanent silent scream. Whatever this person had been before the Epidemic, they were gone now. Just a shell full of broken Resolve and rage.

Tetsu rolled left, barrier shattering as he moved. His lungs burned. His reactions were sluggish. Three hours of sleep. Aka was right. He hated when Aka was right.

The Lost lunged again, faster this time.

Tetsu raised his hand‚Äî

Too slow.

Claws raked across his shoulder, tearing through fabric and skin. Blood sprayed hot across his face. The compression in his chest intensified, his Core screaming at him to stop, to breathe, to let go‚Äî

"Move," Aka snapped.

"I said I've got‚Äî"

"You don't have SHIT. Switch. Now."

The Lost's next attack came low, aiming for his legs. Tetsu tried to dodge. His body betrayed him‚Äîexhaustion, blood loss, Core strain. He stumbled.

The creature's hand wrapped around his ankle.

And squeezed.

Bone cracked.

Tetsu's scream tore through the abandoned district, bouncing off hollow buildings and shattered windows. His vision whited out for half a second. When it cleared, the Lost was pulling him closer, claws digging trenches in the asphalt, mouth opening impossibly wide‚Äî

"Enough."

Aka's voice dropped an octave.

And Tetsu felt himself fall backward inside his own skull.

The world snapped back into focus.

Same body. Different driver.

Aka rolled his‚Äîtheir‚Äîshoulder, testing the damage. Blood soaked through the uniform. The ankle was fucked. He could feel bone fragments grinding together.

"Tch. Idiot."

The Lost lunged.

Aka didn't dodge.

Black-red Resolve exploded outward, raw and violent, pressure alone forcing the creature to stumble mid-strike. Momentum Surge flooded their muscles, overwriting pain with pure kinetic force.

The Lost recovered, shrieking, attacking again‚Äî

Aka caught its wrist.

"My turn."

He pivoted, using the creature's momentum against it, and slammed it face-first into the ground hard enough to crater the asphalt. The Lost twitched, tried to rise‚Äî

Aka's foot came down on its spine.

Crack.

Once more.

Crack.

The Lost stopped moving.

For a moment, there was only the sound of Aka's breathing‚Äîsteady, controlled‚Äîand the distant wail of sirens.

He looked down at the body. Broken. Pitiful.

"Should've let me drive from the start," he muttered, flexing their damaged hand. "Now look at us."

Footsteps behind him.

"Mikage!"

Aka turned his head slightly. Three figures sprinting toward him across the ruins‚ÄîKaito's flame-orange aura flickering anxiously, Sara's violet lightning crackling along her arms, Daichi already preparing his healing flames.

"He's fine," Aka called out, voice flat. "Mostly."

Kaito skidded to a stop ten feet away, eyes wide. "Holy shit, is that‚Äîdid you‚Äî"

"Yeah. It's handled."

Sara's gaze locked onto him, sharp and assessing. "That's not Tetsu."

Aka smiled, cold and humorless. "Smart girl."

Daichi moved closer, hands raised cautiously. "Can you switch back? I need to treat him before‚Äî"

"Before what? He passes out?" Aka tilted their head. "Too late. He's already gone. Used up everything trying to prove he didn't need me."

"Aka." Captain Kurosawa's voice cut through the moment like a blade.

The man stood at the edge of the scene, arms crossed, golden aura subdued but unmistakable. His expression was unreadable.

"Sir." Aka didn't bother with respect. Just acknowledgment.

"Report."

"Lost terminated. Mikage's an idiot. That's the report."

Kurosawa's jaw tightened. "Casualties?"

"Just him. Civilians evacuated before we arrived."

"Good." The Captain stepped forward, eyes scanning the damage‚ÄîTetsu's blood on the concrete, the Lost's twisted corpse, the shattered asphalt. "Can he walk?"

"Not with that ankle."

"Then you carry him back."

Aka's smile vanished. "I don't do‚Äî"

"That wasn't a request." Kurosawa's tone didn't rise, but the weight of his Resolve pressed down like gravity doubling. "You share that body. You share the consequences."

For a long moment, Aka stared at him.

Then he sighed, annoyed. "Fine."

He bent down, scooped up the Lost's body‚Äîevidence, protocol, whatever‚Äîand slung it over their shoulder like a sack of rice. With his free hand, he activated Tetsu's comm.

"R7, this is Mikage. Target neutralized. Requesting med evac and cleanup crew."

Static crackled.

Then: "Copy that, Mikage. Transport inbound. ETA three minutes."

Aka glanced at the others. Kaito looked sick. Sara looked calculating. Daichi just looked sad.

"What?" Aka snapped.

"Nothing," Sara said quietly. "Just... be careful with him."

"He's not a fucking doll."

"We know." Daichi stepped closer, healing flames already forming in his palms. "But he's our teammate. And whether you like it or not... so are you."

Aka blinked.

Then turned away, jaw tight. "Whatever. Just fix the ankle before he wakes up whining about it."

As Daichi began working, Aka stared out at the empty district, the ruins of what used to be someone's neighborhood, and felt Tetsu stirring faintly in the back of their shared skull.

Still out. But alive.

"Idiot," Aka muttered again, softer this time.

The transport arrived two minutes later.

END CHAPTER 1

‚úÖ WHAT DID THIS ACCOMPLISH?
Opened with: ‚úì Micro character moment (boot-tying) ‚úì Aka's voice immediately ‚úì INSTANT action (Lost attack) ‚úì Tetsu's struggle shown viscerally ‚úì The switch (brutal, efficient, cold) ‚úì R7 dynamics introduced naturally ‚úì Aka's personality (harsh but protective) ‚úì Captain Kurosawa's authority ‚úì Emotional hook (Aka carrying Tetsu's broken body)

Dialogue hits: ‚úì "Good morning to you too" (Tetsu's exhausted sarcasm) ‚úì "My turn" (Aka's cold efficiency) ‚úì "Smart girl" (Aka's condescension) ‚úì "You share that body. You share the consequences" (Captain's weight) ‚úì "So are you" (Daichi's unexpected inclusion)

Tone established: Dark, visceral, emotional, high-stakes, brotherhood buried under hostility

