5. THE LOST - CRITICAL WORLDBUILDING
You asked:

"on what basis do they kill them?"
"can they really revert back to being human again or what?"
This is HUGE for your story's morality.

üéØ THE LOST - DEFINE THIS NOW:
QUESTION A: Can The Lost be saved/reverted?
OPTION 1: NO - Permanent transformation

Once you become Lost, you can't go back
Their Conviction rejected everything during Epidemic
Core corrupted irreversibly
Killing them = only option
Morally heavy but clear
OPTION 2: MAYBE - Extremely rare reversions

99.9% can't be saved
Handful of cases where someone was "pulled back"
Requires [specific conditions you define]
R7 tries first, kills if impossible
Adds hope but also tragedy (most still die)
OPTION 3: YES - But the process is [terrible/expensive/dangerous]

They CAN be saved theoretically
But requires [massive resources/forbidden technique/sacrifice]
Society chooses execution over cost
Morally darkest option (we kill them because it's cheaper)
OPTION 4: UNKNOWN - Nobody knows if it's possible

No successful reversions recorded
Some believe it's possible, others don't
R7 executes them anyway (orders from above)
Ambiguous, haunting
Which option fits your story?

QUESTION B: What's the criteria for execution?
Who decides a Lost must die?

OPTION 1: Automatic

All Lost are executed upon capture
No trial, no assessment
Just policy
Cold, efficient, dystopian
OPTION 2: Case-by-case

R7 assesses threat level
If Lost shows [specific criteria], they're contained
If too dangerous/violent, execution
Captain makes final call
Gives agency, moral weight to decisions
